<edge source="concept.constancy_fortitude" target="concept.patience" id="edge.concept.constancy_fortitude.part_of.concept.patience">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.constancy_fortitude.part_of.concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.constancy_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d8">Constancy</data>
  <data key="d9">habit</data>
  <data key="d10">part_of</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-constancy-fortitude-part-of-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">afflicteth the soul ." Hence there may be patience in bearing this trial, as in enduring any other sorrows. Accordingly longanimity and constancy are both comprised under patience, in so far as both the delay of the hoped for good (which regards longanimity) and the toil which man endures in persistently accomplishing a good work (which regards constancy) m</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">patience | perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.constancy_fortitude" target="concept.fortitude" id="edge.concept.constancy_fortitude.part_of_fortitude.concept.fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.constancy_fortitude.part_of_fortitude.concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.constancy_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d8">Constancy</data>
  <data key="d9">habit</data>
  <data key="d10">part_of_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-constancy-fortitude-part-of-fortitude-concept-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q137-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ereas constancy makes him persist firmly in good against difficulties arising from any other external hindrances. Hence perseverance takes precedence of constancy as a part of fortitude , because the difficulty arising from continuance of action is more intrinsic to the act of virtue than that which arises from external obstacles.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.effeminacy_perseverance" target="concept.perseverance_virtue" id="edge.concept.effeminacy_perseverance.deficiency_opposed_to.concept.perseverance_virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.effeminacy_perseverance.deficiency_opposed_to.concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.effeminacy_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d8">Effeminacy</data>
  <data key="d9">vice</data>
  <data key="d10">deficiency_opposed_to</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Perseverance (Fortitude Part)</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-effeminacy-perseverance-deficiency-opposed-to-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q138-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">praise because thereby a man does not forsake a good on account of long endurance of difficulties and toils: and it is directly opposed to this, seemingly, for a man to be ready to forsake a good on account of difficulties which he cannot endure. This is what we understand by effeminacy, because a thing is said to</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">opposed_vice | perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.fortitude" target="concept.fortitude_gift" id="edge.concept.fortitude.perfected_by.concept.fortitude_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.fortitude.perfected_by.concept.fortitude_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d8">Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d9">virtue</data>
  <data key="d10">perfected_by</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fortitude_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-fortitude-perfected-by-concept-fortitude-gift-st-ii-ii-q139-a001-ad1</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q139.a001.ad1</data>
  <data key="d16">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d17">ind in the endurance of all perils whatever; but it does not go so far as to give confidence of overcoming all dangers: this belongs to the fortitude that is a gift of the Holy Ghost .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">gift</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.fortitude_gift" target="concept.fortitude" id="edge.concept.fortitude_gift.corresponding_gift_of.concept.fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.fortitude_gift.corresponding_gift_of.concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.fortitude_gift</data>
  <data key="d8">Gift of Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d9">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d10">corresponding_gift_of</data>
