  <data key="d12">Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-precepts-of-fortitude-parts-precept-of-concept-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q140-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q140.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d17">as are necessary for right living. Now in order to live aright man needs not only the principal virtues , but also the secondary and annexed virtues . Wherefore the Divine Law contains precepts not only about the acts of the principal virtues , but also about the acts of the secondary and annexed virtues .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">precept</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136" target="concept.longanimity_fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.treated_in.concept.longanimity_fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.treated_in.concept.longanimity_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 — Patience</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.longanimity_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Longanimity</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-treated-in-concept-longanimity-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q136-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Just as by magnanimity a man has a mind to tend to great things, so by longanimity a man has a mind to tend to something a long way off. Wherefore as magnanimity regards hope, which tends to good , rather than daring, fear, or sorrow, which have evil as their ob</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136" target="concept.patience" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.treated_in.concept.patience">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.treated_in.concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 — Patience</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-treated-in-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">"lest he abandon with an unequal mind the goods whereby he may advance to better things." It is therefore evident that patience is a virtue .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
