  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q138-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:137:1 and II-II:137:2 ), perseverance is deserving of praise because thereby a man does not forsake a good on account of long endurance of difficulties and toils: and it is directly opposed to this, seemingly, for a m</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q138" target="concept.pertinacity_perseverance" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q138.treated_in.concept.pertinacity_perseverance">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q138.treated_in.concept.pertinacity_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q138</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.138 — The vices opposed to perseverance</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.pertinacity_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d12">Pertinacity</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-treated-in-concept-pertinacity-perseverance-st-ii-ii-q138-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">, and the persevering man , as he ought. Hence it is clear that perseverance is commended for observing the mean, while pertinacity is reproved for exceeding the mean, and effeminacy for falling short of it.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">opposed_vice</data>
</edge>
