  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q139.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">serving at the same time a certain fittingness between them. Wherefore he ascribes the fourth beatitude, concerning the hunger and thirst for justice , to the fourth gift , namely fortitude . Yet there is a certain congruity between them, because, as stated ( Article 1 ), fortitude is about difficult things. Now it is very diff</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">gift</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q139" target="concept.counsel_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q139.treated_in.concept.counsel_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q139.treated_in.concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q139</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.139 — The gift of fortitude</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q139-treated-in-concept-counsel-gift-st-ii-ii-q139-a001-ad3</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q139.a001.ad3</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">uring dangers, but also inasmuch as it consists in accomplishing any difficult work. Wherefore the gift of fortitude is directed by the gift of counsel, which seems to be concerned chiefly with the greater goods.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">gift</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q139" target="concept.fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q139.treated_in.concept.fortitude">
