  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">o the good , inasmuch as they safeguard the good of reason against the impulse of the passions . Now among the passions sorrow is strong to hinder the good of reason , according to 2 Corinthians 7:10 , "The sorrow of the world worketh death," and Sirach 30:25 , "Sadness hath killed many, and there is no profit in it." Hence</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a001" target="concept.patience" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a001.treated_in.concept.patience">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a001.treated_in.concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.1 — Is patience a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a001-treated-in-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">"lest he abandon with an unequal mind the goods whereby he may advance to better things." It is therefore evident that patience is a virtue .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a002" target="concept.patience" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a002.treated_in.concept.patience">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a002.treated_in.concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.2 — Is it the greatest of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a002-treated-in-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ouch, with which temperance is concerned, withdraw man from good more than any kind of hardship, which is the object of patience. Therefore patience is not the greatest of the virtues , but falls short, not only of the theological virtues , and of prudence and justice which directly establish man in good ,</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a003" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a003.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a003.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.3 — Can it be had without grace?</data>
