  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a003-treated-in-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">5:5 , "The charity of God is poured forth in our hearts by the Holy Ghost Who is given to us." Therefore it is clearly impossible to have patience without the help of grace .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a004" target="concept.fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a004.treated_in.concept.fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a004.treated_in.concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.4 — Is it a part of fortitude?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a004-treated-in-concept-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q136-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">titude has the principal place, and that it lays claim to that which is principal in this matter. Wherefore patience is annexed to fortitude as secondary to principal virtue , for which reason Prosper calls patience brave (Sent. 811).</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a004" target="concept.patience" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a004.treated_in.concept.patience">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a004.treated_in.concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.4 — Is it a part of fortitude?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a004-treated-in-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Patience is a quasi-potential part of fortitude , because it is annexed thereto as secondary to principal virtue . For it belongs to patience "to suffer with an equal mind the evils inflicted by others," as Gregory says in a ho</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a005" target="concept.constancy_fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a005.treated_in.concept.constancy_fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a005.treated_in.concept.constancy_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.5 — Is it the same as longanimity?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.constancy_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Constancy</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a005-treated-in-concept-constancy-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q136-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">oul ." Hence there may be patience in bearing this trial, as in enduring any other sorrows. Accordingly longanimity and constancy are both comprised under patience, in so far as both the delay of the hoped for good (which regards longanimity) and the toil which man endures in persistently accomplishing a goo</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a005" target="concept.longanimity_fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a005.treated_in.concept.longanimity_fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a005.treated_in.concept.longanimity_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.5 — Is it the same as longanimity?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.longanimity_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Longanimity</data>
  <data key="d13">habit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a005-treated-in-concept-longanimity-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q136-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Just as by magnanimity a man has a mind to tend to great things, so by longanimity a man has a mind to tend to something a long way off. Wherefore as magnanimity regards hope, which tends to good , rather than daring, fear, or sorrow, which have evil as their ob</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q136.a005" target="concept.patience" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a005.treated_in.concept.patience">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q136.a005.treated_in.concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q136.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.136 a.5 — Is it the same as longanimity?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.patience</data>
  <data key="d12">Patience</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q136-a005-treated-in-concept-patience-st-ii-ii-q136-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q136.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ch have evil as their object, so also does longanimity. Hence longanimity has more in common with magnanimity than with patience. Nevertheless it may have something in common with patience, for two reasons. First, because patience, like fortitude , endures certain evils for the sake of good , and if this go</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">patience</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a001" target="concept.continuance_in_good" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a001.treated_in.concept.continuance_in_good">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a001.treated_in.concept.continuance_in_good</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.137 a.1 — Is perseverance a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.continuance_in_good</data>
  <data key="d12">Continuance in Good</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a001-treated-in-concept-continuance-in-good-st-ii-ii-q137-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">secondly, from the length of time, since to persist long in something difficult involves a special difficulty. Hence to persist long in something good until it is accomplished belongs to a special virtue . Accordingly just as temperance and fortitude are special virtues , for the reason that the one moderates pleasures of touch</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a001" target="concept.perseverance_virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a001.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a001.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.137 a.1 — Is perseverance a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Perseverance (Fortitude Part)</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a001-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q137-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e other moderates fear and daring in connection with dangers of death (which also is something difficult in itself), so perseverance is a special virtue , since it consists in enduring delays in the above or other virtuous deeds , so far as necessity requires.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a002" target="concept.fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a002.treated_in.concept.fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a002.treated_in.concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.137 a.2 — Is it a part of fortitude?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fortitude</data>
  <data key="d12">Fortitude</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a002-treated-in-concept-fortitude-st-ii-ii-q137-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ollows of necessity that every virtue which has a title to praise for the firm endurance of something difficult must be annexed to fortitude as secondary to principal virtue . Now the endurance of difficulty arising from delay in accomplishing a good work gives perseverance its claim to praise: nor is this so difficult</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a002" target="concept.perseverance_virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a002.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a002.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.137 a.2 — Is it a part of fortitude?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Perseverance (Fortitude Part)</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a002-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q137-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">g a good work gives perseverance its claim to praise: nor is this so difficult as to endure dangers of death. Therefore perseverance is annexed to fortitude , as secondary to principal virtue .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a003" target="concept.constancy_fortitude" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a003.treated_in.concept.constancy_fortitude">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a003.treated_in.concept.constancy_fortitude</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a003</data>
