  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a003-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q137-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Perseverance and constancy agree as to end, since it belongs to both to persist firmly in some good : but they differ as to those things which make it difficult to persist in good . Because the virtue of pe</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a004" target="concept.grace" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a004.treated_in.concept.grace">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a004.treated_in.concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.137 a.4 — Does it need the help of grace?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.grace</data>
  <data key="d12">Grace</data>
  <data key="d13">grace</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a004-treated-in-concept-grace-st-ii-ii-q137-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">rance has a twofold signification. First, it denotes the habit of perseverance, considered as a virtue . On this way it needs the gift of habitual grace , even as the other infused virtues . Secondly, it may be taken to denote the act of perseverance enduring until death: and in this sense it needs not only habitual grace , but al</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q137.a004" target="concept.perseverance_virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a004.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q137.a004.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q137.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.137 a.4 — Does it need the help of grace?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Perseverance (Fortitude Part)</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q137-a004-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q137-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q137.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ply to Objection 2 ; Article 2, Reply to Objection 3 ), perseverance has a twofold signification. First, it denotes the habit of perseverance, considered as a virtue . On this way it needs the gift of habitual grace , even as the other infused virtues . Secondly, it may be taken to denote the act of perseverance endurin</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q138.a001" target="concept.effeminacy_perseverance" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a001.treated_in.concept.effeminacy_perseverance">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a001.treated_in.concept.effeminacy_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q138.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.138 a.1 — Effeminacy</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.effeminacy_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d12">Effeminacy</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-a001-treated-in-concept-effeminacy-perseverance-st-ii-ii-q138-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">or a man to be ready to forsake a good on account of difficulties which he cannot endure. This is what we understand by effeminacy, because a thing is said to be "soft" if it readily yields to the touch. Now a thing is not declared to be soft through yielding to a heavy blow, for walls yield to the battering-</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">opposed_vice</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q138.a001" target="concept.perseverance_virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a001.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a001.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q138.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.138 a.1 — Effeminacy</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Perseverance (Fortitude Part)</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-a001-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q138-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:137:1 and II-II:137:2 ), perseverance is deserving of praise because thereby a man does not forsake a good on account of long endurance of difficulties and toils: and it is directly opposed to this, seemingly, for a man to be ready to f</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q138.a002" target="concept.perseverance_virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a002.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a002.treated_in.concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q138.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.138 a.2 — Pertinacity</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.perseverance_virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Perseverance (Fortitude Part)</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-a002-treated-in-concept-perseverance-virtue-st-ii-ii-q138-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As Isidore says (Etym. x) "a person is said to be pertinacious who holds on impudently, as being utterly tenacious." "Pervicacious" has the same meaning, for it signifies that a man "perseveres in his purpose until he is victorious: for the ancients called 'vi</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">perseverance</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q138.a002" target="concept.pertinacity_perseverance" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a002.treated_in.concept.pertinacity_perseverance">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a002.treated_in.concept.pertinacity_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q138.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.138 a.2 — Pertinacity</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.pertinacity_perseverance</data>
  <data key="d12">Pertinacity</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-a002-treated-in-concept-pertinacity-perseverance-st-ii-ii-q138-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">, and the persevering man , as he ought. Hence it is clear that perseverance is commended for observing the mean, while pertinacity is reproved for exceeding the mean, and effeminacy for falling short of it.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">opposed_vice</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q138.a002" target="concept.vainglory" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a002.treated_in.concept.vainglory">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q138.a002.treated_in.concept.vainglory</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q138.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.138 a.2 — Pertinacity</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.vainglory</data>
  <data key="d12">Vainglory</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q138-a002-treated-in-concept-vainglory-st-ii-ii-q138-a002-ad1</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q138.a002.ad1</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">sistent in his own opinion, is that he wishes by this means to make a show of his own excellence: wherefore this is the result of vainglory as its cause . Now it has been stated above ( II-II:127:2 ad 1 ; II-II:133:2 ), that opposition of vices to virtues depends, not on their cause , but on their species .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">opposed_vice</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q139.a001" target="concept.arduous_work" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q139.a001.treated_in.concept.arduous_work">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q139.a001.treated_in.concept.arduous_work</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q139.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.139 a.1 — Is fortitude a gift?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.arduous_work</data>
  <data key="d12">Arduous / Difficult Work</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q139-a001-treated-in-concept-arduous-work-st-ii-ii-q139-a001-ad3</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q139.a001.ad3</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e regards the virtue of fortitude not only because it consists in enduring dangers, but also inasmuch as it consists in accomplishing any difficult work. Wherefore the gift of fortitude is directed by the gift of counsel, which seems to be concerned chiefly with the greater goods.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d19">gift</data>
</edge>
